00:08:56,650 --> 00:08:58,670
Risk and safety for free diving.

139
00:09:00,360 --> 00:09:02,920
One of the biggest risks is blackout.

140
00:09:02,920 --> 00:09:04,190
In extreme diving and

141
00:09:04,190 --> 00:09:08,810
competition, divers are trying to push the
limits of tolerance underwater.

142
00:09:08,810 --> 00:09:13,080
If they misjudge and don't make it back to
the surface before their oxygen runs out,

143
00:09:13,080 --> 00:09:15,430
they can black out underwater.

144
00:09:15,430 --> 00:09:18,700
Usually this happens near the surface
because they haven't quite made it

145
00:09:18,700 --> 00:09:20,380
all the way back up.

146
00:09:20,380 --> 00:09:21,450
It's much more rare for

147
00:09:21,450 --> 00:09:24,290
it to happen in deep water unless
something goes terribly wrong.

148
00:09:25,570 --> 00:09:27,050
Because of the blackout risk,

149
00:09:27,050 --> 00:09:32,590
free divers never go down without a safety
diver watching them continuously.

150
00:09:32,590 --> 00:09:36,410
If the first diver passes out, the safety
diver will cover their mouth and

151
00:09:36,410 --> 00:09:38,090
nose to prevent inhalation and

152
00:09:38,090 --> 00:09:41,720
pull the diver to the surface; where they
will automatically start breathing again.

153
00:09:43,810 --> 00:09:46,880
Second on the list is respiratory squeeze.

154
00:09:46,880 --> 00:09:50,357
When tissues are squeezed in response to
the increasing pressure,

155
00:09:50,357 --> 00:09:52,126
whether they're compressible or

156
00:09:52,126 --> 00:09:56,126
non-compressible, they can get damaged and
start to leak fluid and blood.

157
00:09:56,126 --> 00:10:01,555
Trachea, lungs, sinuses, nose, even the
space covered by the mask,

158
00:10:01,555 --> 00:10:04,543
can all suffer barotrauma and damage.

159
00:10:04,543 --> 00:10:08,063
Although getting squeezed rarely results
in permanent damage,

160
00:10:08,063 --> 00:10:11,967
lung squeeze was thought to have
contributed to the recent free diving,

161
00:10:11,967 --> 00:10:15,108
diving death of Nicholas Mevoli in
November 2013.

162
00:10:16,700 --> 00:10:20,740
The good news is that free diving doesn't
have the same risks as sc,

163
00:10:20,740 --> 00:10:25,240
scuba in terms of gas toxicity and
decompression issues.

164
00:10:25,240 --> 00:10:30,740
The short duration underwater and minimal
available oxygen reduce these risks.

165
00:10:30,740 --> 00:10:34,160
It takes significant training in order to
free dive long enough and

166
00:10:34,160 --> 00:10:36,249
deep enough to get decompression sickness.

167
00:10:37,350 --> 00:10:42,990
However, nitrogen can accumulate over time
in the blood during many repeat dives,

168
00:10:42,990 --> 00:10:46,330
so appropriate precaution should still be
taken in that situation.

